For emphyteusis, see 3 ξ 145. Although an emphyteusis might be of unlimited duration, and was alienable without the consent of the proprietor, yet the proprietor had a reversion on failure of the heirs of the emphyteuta, just as the feudal lord of a fee has the reversion on failure of the heirs of the tenant in fee. Accordingly, emphyteusis is regarded as the model on which feudal tenure was instituted. This reversion or escheat to the lord of the fee makes property inland theoretically imperfect, and, like emphyteusiS, rather a jus in re aliena than plenary dominion. Property in chatteIS, on the contrary, has no reversioner interposed between the proprietot and the sovereign as ultimus heres, and, therefore, is absolute.
